<article>
    <h1>Dy&#xAD;nasty</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200913/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-13"><time>2020-09-13</time></a>
        - <span>INSIGHT</span>
        - <span role="byline">Walt&#xAD;sim@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>A 2015 paper in the Ja­panese Jour­nal of Po­lit­i­cal Sci­ence, not­ing that the lop­sided con­test would hin­der the growth of fresh pol­icy ideas, ob­served: “Po­lit­i­cal dy­nas­ties have a neg­a­tive con­se­quence for demo­cratic pol­i­cy­mak­ing.”</p>
    <p>the lop­sided con­test would hin­der the growth of fresh pol­icy ideas, ob­served: “Po­lit­i­cal dy­nas­ties have a neg­a­tive con­se­quence for demo­cratic pol­i­cy­mak­ing.”</p>
    <p>But Dr Uchiyama points to the chang­ing na­ture of Ja­panese pol­i­tics since, in which hered­i­tary politi­cians no longer ride on their par­ents’ coat-tails but are pop­u­lar on their own merit. Ex­am­ples in the Cabi­net in­clude De­fence Min­is­ter Taro Kono, 57. His fa­ther Yo­hei Kono had de­liv­ered in 1993 what has come to be known as the “Kono State­ment”. It was Ja­pan’s first ac­knowl­edge­ment of wartime com­fort women.</p>
    <p>The younger Mr Kono, who has gained a social me­dia fol­low­ing, is flu­ent in English and seen as a newage politi­cian who speaks his mind.</p>
    <p>He also won credit for ditch­ing plans to de­ploy the US-made Aegis Ashore mis­sile de­fence sys­tem, ac­knowl­edg­ing that the gov­ern­ment had not done enough due dili­gence.</p>
    <p>And then there is En­vi­ron­ment Min­is­ter Shin­jiro Koizumi, 39, the son of for­mer prime min­is­ter Ju­nichiro Koizumi, who ruled from 2001 and 2006, be­fore hand­ing over the reins to Mr Abe.</p>
    <p>The younger Mr Koizumi projects him­self as a pro­gres­sive, by tak­ing pa­ter­nity leave when his first son was born this year, and by tak­ing steps to tear down the coun­try’s long as­so­ci­a­tion with coal.</p>
    <p>In­ci­den­tally, both men have their eyes set on the prime min­is­ter job.</p>

